\chapter{Results and discussion}

\section{Flowering plant communities' diversity}

During the entire sampling period, 117 flowering species were recorded, distributed across 42 plant families (Table \ref{tab:flowering flora}).

In particular 2 families are dominant in the area.

\begin{itemize}
	\item Asteraceae with 22 species is the most represented family, this is a large angiosperm family, it is characterized by the typical inflorescence (flower heads) and one-seeded achene fruits. Species belonging to this family present nectar within the corolla tube which is thus readily available to many kinds of insect visitors \parencite{faegriPrinciplesPollinationEcology2013}. Species like \textit{Helminthotheca echioides} L., \textit{Dittrichia viscosa} L., and \textit{Sonchus asper} L. were particularly abundant. These are typical of disturbed or agriculture affected habitats and contribute significantly to pollinator resources throughout the season.\\
	
	\item Fabaceae with 19 species is the second most abundant family, it includes  legumes such as Trifolium, Vicia, and Medicago species. The family presents specialized pollen presentation and resease mechanism, these characteristics function as complementary filters, optimizing pollinator efficiency and excluding ineffective visitors \parencite{zhaoSynergisticEffectsFlower2025}. For example in faba bean the major contributors to pollen transport are honeybees, solitary bees and short-tangue bumblebees \parencite{lundinPartitioningPollinationServices2023}. Floral visitors are usually more specialized than in the Asteraceae family, in fact, Fabaceae are typically pollinated by the bee functional group. Legume species are also  crucial for soil fertility in agricultural areas for their nitrogen-fixing capacity \parencite{bardaFlowerMorphologyNectar2024}. 
\end{itemize}


Other well-represented families include Brassicaceae (5 species), which are early bloomers, often dominant in spring; Lamiaceae (8 species), which are mainly aromatic herbs  with specialized pollination syndromes, and Rosaceae and Ranunculaceae species that contribute to mid- and late-season flowering.

The presence of species from families with staggered flowering times (e.g., Asteraceae, Fabaceae, Brassicaceae) ensures continuous floral availability from early spring to late autumn. And the mix of herbaceous, shrubby, and climbing species (e.g., \textit{Clematis vitalba} L., \textit{Rubus ulmifolius} Schott, \textit{Pistacia lentiscus} L.) assures distinct floral resources. The flora includes species adapted to different pollination strategies, some are generalists (e.g., \textit{Cichorium intybus} L., \textit{Foeniculum vulgare} L.) and other have more specific flower adaptation for pollination like \textit{Ophrys sphegodes} Mill. (Orchidaceae family). 


So this floral diversity makes the landscape heterogeneous also from a functional ecology perspective (different strategies, phenologies, and habitat preferences). 






