Regardless to the floral composition, the floral density was significantly different among habitats ($\chi^2$ = 9.11, df = 2, p < 0.05). Subsequent pairwise comparisons revealed that while Meadow and Maquis habitats had similar floral cover abundance (p > 0.05), both differed significantly from Riparian habitat (Meadow-Riparian: p < 0.05; Maquis-Riparian: p < 0.01). See Table \ref{tab:kruskal_results} for details. This suggests that despite geographic proximity, the riparian zone is characterized by poor floral resources.

Meadow was the most diverse plant community considering Shannon and Simpson diversity indices, followed by Maquis and Riparian. Pielou's evenness is also maximum in Meadow (Figure \ref{fig:alpha indices}), revealing that the flowers of different species are more equally distributed in Meadow compared to Maquis. Riparian, on the other hand, has an evenness similar to Meadow but lower diversity due to an overall smaller number of species and fewer floral units. Hutcheson's t-tests revealed highly significant differences in Shannon diversity among all the three habitat types (all pairwise comparisons: p < 0.001). 

\paragraph{Maquis}
In Maquis, a total of 31 plant species were recorded in flower during the study, with a peak in September and a low in spring. The number of floral units is highest in May, and it is represented by the biggest absolute value among habitats. Floral units density reaches the maximum in Maquis with 86.2 pollination units per square meter (Table \ref{tab:alpha.spacial.table}).

Even though Maquis exhibited the highest species richness ($S = 31$) it presents lower evenness ($J' = 0.64$), indicating a community dominated by a few abundant species alongside many rare species. Shannon index ($H' = 2.20$) indicates a relatively high diversity rate but significantly smaller than that in Meadow. Simpson index ($D = 0.83$) is similar to Riparian value proving the dominance of certain species in the community. This pattern is typical of Mediterranean shrublands where some competitive dominants structure the community, so it may be acting as pollination “hotspots” but usually in a specific time of the year, in this case spring, making it crucial for early-season pollinators in the area (Figure \ref{fig:alpha indices}).


\paragraph{Meadow}

In Meadow, a total of 27 plant species were recorded in flower during the study. Richness peaks in August and it reaches its lowest values in spring. The total of floral units counted is smaller than Maquis' (Table \ref{tab:alpha.spacial.table}).

Meadow exhibits the highest diversity ($H' = 2.60$, $D = 0.91$) despite a slightly lower richness compared to Maquis. In fact, the highest evenness ($J' = 0.79$) indicates more equitable species abundances, suggesting reduced competitive exclusion. This pattern may result from an heterogeneous resource distribution characteristic of open grasslands, also offering a more reliable source of nourishment for visitors (Figure \ref{fig:alpha indices}).


\paragraph{Riparian}

In Riparian, only 13 plant species were recorded in flower during the study, the lowest value among the considered habitat types.
This habitat presents the lowest availability of floral resources in terms of number of species and density (Table \ref{tab:alpha.spacial.table}). 

The Riparian site has a steady but very low richness of species in flower. It is the less diverse area ($H' = 2.00$, $D = 0.82$). It exhibits a moderate evenness ($J' = 0.78$), more equitable species abundances than Maquis. It reflects a more harsh environment for flower visitors offering limited resources (Figure \ref{fig:alpha indices}).  


\subsection{Temporal variation}

Considering the integrated area, all months April to October have a number of species in flower that ranges between 16 and 9, the maximum is reached in June followed by May (when the species present are 13). Floral abundances follow a slightly different pattern, density is by far highest in May (Figure \ref{fig:Monthly abundances}), but Kruskal-Wallis test revealed that the pattern of floral units abundances doesn't differ significantly across months (p > 0.5). 

The temporal pattern of diversity metrics (Figure \ref{fig:Monthly variation of Shannon diversity index}) shows how all months have similar alpha diversity except for May. This month, despite the highest floral abundance, presents low diversity compared to other months, in fact evenness is also very low, showing that the area has a few dominant species. The total number of flower units found in May is 2412, with 1881 flowers belonging to \textit{Sulla coronaria} (L.) B.H.Choi \& H.Ohashi. Pairwise Hutcheson t-tests  revealed that May exhibited the most distinct diversity pattern, being significantly different from all other months (p < 0.001 for all comparisons).
The test also showed significant differences in Shannon diversity between most monthly comparisons (19 out of 21 comparisons, p < 0.05). However, no significant difference was found between June-July (p > 0.05), and April-July showed only borderline significance (p = 0.053).

The trend is typical of  Mediterranean habitats where in spring a burst of flowering and germination follows the begin of rains. The decline in summer is likely due to the dry season limits. Usually there would be an Autumn recovery, consequence of cooler temperatures and higher humidity, but it wasn't registered when only considering flowering flora and floral units.  
The values are overall low which may reflect habitat simplification due to agriculture use.

