\paragraph{Maquis}

The Maquis network in Figure \ref{fig:plotweb.maquis} counts with 219 interactions, between six insect functional groups and 25 plant species mainly distributed within the families Lamiaceae, Asteraceae, Fabaceae, and Rosaceae. Some plant species attract multiple pollinator groups, most visits happened on just 4 species, \textit{Cephalaria transsylvanica} L., \textit{Torilis arvensis} (Huds.) Link and \textit{Cistus tauricus} C.Presl, \textit{Verbena officinalis} L.. Other species like \textit{Sideritis romana} L. or \textit{Rubus ulmifolius} Schott show limited and/or specialized connections.  Bees and hoverflies dominate the interactions, showing broad connectivity across many plant species. Beetles, bee flies, and butterflies exhibit narrower interaction profiles, suggesting more selective visitation or lower abundance. Moths are completely absent.

Considering the pollination network metrics in Table \ref{tab:metrics_spacial_table}, the Maquis habitat exhibits similar Shannon diversity (3.16) and Pielou's evenness (0.63) to Meadow, indicating that interactions are numerous and fairly equally distributed among taxa, creating a balanced pollination system. Robustness is the highest among habitats (0.86), demonstrating exceptional resistance to species loss cascades. This resilience is directly linked to the lowest specialization level ($H2 = 0.30$), where generalized interactions provide extensive redundancy buffers. Nestedness is moderate (25.43), revealing the existence of a hierarchical structure that strengthens the resilience of the system to species loss. Despite this organization, functional complementarity ($FC$) is the highest (192.48) among the three habitats, showing that this one is the habitat type with highest structural complexity that allows a good niche partitioning among species. 

