\paragraph{Riparian}

The riparian network in Figure \ref{fig:plotweb.riparian} captures only 134 interactions between six insect functional groups and 11 plant species typical of riparian zones. With a dominance of Apiaceae, Asteraceae, and Boraginaceae. Some species like \textit{Convolvulus arvensis} L., \textit{Torilis arvensis} (Huds.) Link, or \textit{Daucus carota} L. show multiple connections but many plant species interact with just one insect functional group. Bees and beetles dominate the network, this time beetles are even more present than bees. Butterflies, wasps, bee flies and hoverflies are present with moderate interaction breadth. Moths are completely absent. 

The Riparian habitat's network displays the lowest Shannon diversity (2.47) with reduced evenness (0.59), reflecting fewer interactions that are more unevenly distributed among species. Robustness is the lowest (0.70), indicating higher vulnerability to species loss cascades. This aligns with the highest specialization level ($H2 = 0.58$), where species engage in more exclusive interactions with limited redundancy. Nestedness is the highest (30.49), revealing a strongly hierarchical structure that efficiently organizes specialized interactions. Functional complementarity is the lowest (142.27) among habitat types as well, showing higher functional redundancy where species share ecological niches since this area is the less diverse of all and offers less resources for pollinators (Table \ref{tab:metrics_spacial_table}).


